name: 4-acetylbenzonitrile
Reason: The base structure for 4-acetylbenzonitrile is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C. Acetyl group substitution generally increases the melting point due to the presence of the carbonyl function which can participate in dipolar interactions and possible hydrogen bonding if there are suitable hydrogen bond donors. However, in this case, acetyl group is electron-withdrawing which can have a converse effect in solid state, decreasing the melting point. The nitrile group is also an electron-withdrawing group and can participate in dipolar interactions but typically has a smaller effect on melting point compared to the acetyl group. Overall, the acetyl group will increase the melting point whereas the nitrile group will probably have a lesser effect. Considering the cumulative effects of the electron-withdrawing acetyl group (~+20), and the slightly stabilizing effect of the nitrile group (~+5 to 10), a moderately higher melting point can be predicted.
